DOCUMENT();
loadMacros( "PGbasicmacros.pl",
                "MathObjects.pl",
	        "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
	        "PGchoicemacros.pl",
	        "PGanswermacros.pl",
                "PG_CAPAmacros.pl",
    		"BrockPhysicsMacros.pl",
                "answerHints.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;
$showHint =3;

$temp = random(350,500,0.1);
$eff = random(10,25,0.1);
$temp2 = random(100,200,0.1);
$A1 = (((1)-($eff/100))*($temp+273.15))-273.15;
$A2 = ((1)-(($temp2+273.15)/($temp+273.15)))*(100);

Context() -> texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT

$PAR

<b>If you do not answer this question correctly in $showHint attempts, you can get a hint.</b>

$PAR

Steam locomotives have an efficiency of \($eff\)\(\textrm{%}\) and operate with a hot steam temperature of \($temp^{\circ}\textrm{C}\) .

$PAR

a) What would the cold reservoir temperature be if this were a Carnot engine?

$PAR

\{ans_rule(40)\} \(^{\circ}\textrm{C}\)

$PAR

END_TEXT
BEGIN_HINT
Can you rearrange the formula for the efficiency of a Carnot engine to solve for the cold reservoir temperature? To what scale must you first convert the given temperature?
END_HINT

ANS(num_cmp("$A1"));

BEGIN_TEXT

$PAR

b) What would the maximum efficiency of this steam engine be if its cold reservoir temperature were \($temp2^{\circ}\textrm{C}\)?

$PAR

\{ans_rule(40)\} \(\textrm{%}\)

$PAR

END_TEXT

Context() -> normalStrings;

ANS(num_cmp("$A2"));


